</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="96" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="96">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="96">
This species is the best known of the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Townsendiella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Townsendiella" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Townsendiella</taxonomicName>
, given the extensive life history work conducted on it and its host (
<bibRefCitation author="Rozen, JG Jr" journalOrPublisher="American Museum Novitates" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" pagination="1 - 11" title="Biology and larvae of the cleptoparasitic bee Townsendiellapulchra and nesting biology of its host Hesperapislarreae (Hymenoptera: Apoidea)." volume="3005" year="1991">Rozen and McGinley 1991</bibRefCitation>
). It will be interesting to see if all 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Townsendiella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Townsendiella" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Townsendiella</taxonomicName>
share similar life histories, once such information becomes available for the remaining species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
